COMP 2012 Object-Oriented Programming and Data Structures

Lab 2 Constructor & Destructor

Overview

To practice with C++ constructors and destructors, we will build a simulation of a small library. The library contains some bookcases, which can hold a number of different books. All of these will be represented with C++ classes, and you will need to finish the constructors and destructors of them accordingly.

You can download the source files in a zip package HERE.

The following classes are given in library.h, and the member functions will need to be implemented in library.cpp: 

class Book {
  private:
      char* name;
      char* author;
      int publishYear;
  
  public:
      Book(const char* name, const char* author, int publishYear);
      ~Book();

      void printInfo() const {
        // Already implemented
      }
};

class Bookcase {
  private:
      Book** books;
      int numBooks;
      const int capacity;
  
  public:
      Bookcase(int capacity);
      ~Bookcase();

      void addBook(const char* name, const char* author, int publishYear);

      void showContent() const {
        // Already implemented
      }
};

enum BookcaseID { SCIENCE, HUMANITIES, MISC, NUM_OF_BOOKCASES };

class Library {
  private:
      Bookcase bookcases[NUM_OF_BOOKCASES];
  
  public:
      Library(int sciCapacity, int hmnCapacity, int miscCapacity);
      ~Library();

      void addBook(const char* name, const char* author, int publishYear, BookcaseID id) {
          if (id == NUM_OF_BOOKCASES) return;
          bookcases[id].addBook(name, author, publishYear);
      }

      void showAllBooks() const {
        // Already implemented
      }
};

The class Book represents a book containing information about its name, author and publishing year. Note that unlike lab 1, the strings here are stored as C-strings (array of char). The library cstring is included, allowing you to use strlen and strcpy to copy the contents of the parameter C-strings into the attributes.

The class Bookcase represents a bookcase, which can contain books. Each bookcase can have some capacity - for example, a bookcase with a capacity of 10 can hold at most 10 books, but the actual number of books can be anywhere from 0 to 10. The bookcase is initially empty when constructed, and books can be added to the bookcase afterwards.

The class Library represents a library. The library in this lab contains 3 bookcases: one for Science books, one for Humanities books and one for other types of books. We have defined an enum to assign readable names to the index of the bookcases - for example, MISC equals 2, so bookcases[MISC] is the 3rd bookcase in the library. The function to add a book to one of the bookcases has been implemented for you.

Lab Tasks

Your task is to implement the functions in library.cpp (TODO 1 ~ TODO 7).

TODO 1: Book constructor
Initialize the data members name, author and publishYear. You need to use the strlen and strcpy library functions to perform string copying.
TODO 2: Book destructor
De-allocate any dynamic memory in this object.
TODO 3: Bookcase constructor
Construct an empty Bookcase with the specified capacity. This means books is initialized as an array with size capacity, and numBooks is set to 0. The constant data member capacity should also be set to the provided parameter.
Hint: Review the lecture notes on the Member Initializer List.

TODO 4: Bookcase destructor
De-allocate any dynamic memory in this object. It is important to note that new Books will be created in the addBook function.
TODO 5: Finish the implementation of Bookcase::addBook(const char* name, const char* author, int publishYear)
  • If the bookcase capacity is reached, the function prints a message and exits. Complete the if statement for this case.
  • Otherwise, create a dynamic Book object with the specified parameters, and assign the books pointer at index numBooks to point to it. Then, increment numBooks.
TODO 6: Library constructor
Initialize the data member bookcases. Note that this data member is a non-dynamic array. The parameters represent the capacity of the 3 bookcases, which must be used to construct the bookcases.
Hint: Review the lecture notes on the Member Initializer List.

TODO 7: Library destructor
De-allocate any dynamic memory in this object.

Compile and Test

After you have finished all tasks (TODO 1 ~ TODO 7), you can compile the files by typing g++ *.cpp -Wall -std=c++11 -o lab2.exe in the terminal to produce the executable lab2.exe. Your program must be able to re-generate exactly the same output as the sample output that has been shown in the overview section. You should read the main.cpp file carefully to understand how the sample output is generated.

Submission Deadline and Guidelines:

The lab assignment is due 10 minutes after the end of your lab session.
We will use an online grading system, ZINC, to grade your lab work. Please upload the following files as a .zip file to ZINC: 
- library.cpp
Please remember to zip the files directly, NOT zip a folder with the required files. Alternatively, you may upload this single file directly to ZINC. After submitting, please review the ZINC report to make sure your submission is parsed correctly. You can make multiple submissions to ZINC before the deadline. Only the last submission will be graded.

Note: The ZINC score report contains 3 test cases numbered #1, #2 and #3. There are 3 additional test cases #11, #12 and #13, which are the same as the first 3 test cases, but the program is compiled using the -fsanitize flag. You will lose points for these test cases if your program contains memory leak or other runtime issues.
